    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4019822212" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4019822212" />
    <a title="Sallie Dunn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32091911-sallie-dunn"><img alt="Sallie Dunn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597761548p2/32091911.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4019822212?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sallie Dunn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sallie Dunn" href="/user/show/32091911-sallie-dunn">Sallie Dunn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" " href="/book/show/18284169-conversation-in-the-cathedral">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4019822212" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12228973437031654257">Conversations in the Cathedral is a largely political novel, and a very pessimistic one at that. This book was a book club choice, and I can’t honestly say that I would ever have read it otherwise. This author has won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 2010. The book is long and difficult. The author portrays Peruvian society in the years of the Odria dictatorship (1948 thru 1956) and its disastrous effect on Peruvian society as a whole. The main character in this book is Santiago Zavala (aka Skin</span>
  <span id="freeText12228973437031654257" style="display:none">Conversations in the Cathedral is a largely political novel, and a very pessimistic one at that. This book was a book club choice, and I can’t honestly say that I would ever have read it otherwise. This author has won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 2010. The book is long and difficult. The author portrays Peruvian society in the years of the Odria dictatorship (1948 thru 1956) and its disastrous effect on Peruvian society as a whole. The main character in this book is Santiago Zavala (aka Skinny and Zavalita). He is the favorite son of Fermin Zavala who is a wealthy Peruvian industrialist. Fermin has ties to the Odria regime; he is also a homosexual, which his son does not know when the book begins. Another important character in the book is Ambrosio Pardah, who was a childhood friend of Santiago’s. Ambrosio is part black and part Indian, and the racial tensions in Peruvian society are on full display throughout the book. Ambrosio is a dog catcher when the book opens, but he had been a chauffeur to both Cayo Bermudez and Fermin Zavala. There is a wealthy prostitute as well as a mulatto prostitute. They engage in a lesbian relationship so that Cayo Bermudez, the right hand man of General Manuel Odria, can be a voyeur to said relationship. Of course, there is much more to this story and again, I caution you that its long and difficult. I would not have been able to write this review without looking up lots of literary discussion of it. Although I generally have the greatest respect for Nobel Prize authors and try to read at least some of their works, I would give this particular novel three stars. I acknowledge that it was brilliant, but difficult for me to comprehend.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12228973437031654257" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

