        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2998195635" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17697147043659738548">I will not lie. It&apos;s not Mario Vargas Llosa&apos;s essential novel <b>The Time of the Hero</b>--the winner of the Nobel Prize, the literary inspiration that made me go to Peru. It is the adventure of my beloved reporter Tintin in <b>Prisoners of the Sun</b>. Ha-ha.<br/><br/>The first time I read it when I was nine at the local library, Herge&apos;s comic had persuaded me to dream that someday I must go to the <b>Andes Mountain</b>. And now, I stand on the sacred hill to feel every bead of sweat and every ache of sunburn, to witness the</span>
  <span id="freeText17697147043659738548" style="display:none">I will not lie. It's not Mario Vargas Llosa's essential novel <b>The Time of the Hero</b>--the winner of the Nobel Prize, the literary inspiration that made me go to Peru. It is the adventure of my beloved reporter Tintin in <b>Prisoners of the Sun</b>. Ha-ha.<br /><br />The first time I read it when I was nine at the local library, Herge's comic had persuaded me to dream that someday I must go to the <b>Andes Mountain</b>. And now, I stand on the sacred hill to feel every bead of sweat and every ache of sunburn, to witness the sea of trees and admire the waves of the hills, and see the elusive ruined citadel <b>Machu Picchu</b>, I just feel that my life has been half fulfilled.<br /><br />Just as <b>Tintin in Tibet</b> that encouraged me to go to the Himalayas last year, Tintin in his spontaneous great adventure <b>Prisoners of the Sun</b>, risked his life to save his friends. Tintin and his companions were attacked by anacondas, wild condor, and alligators. Captain Haddock, Professor Calculus, Thomson &amp; Thompson are very funny, clumsy, and witty as always.<br /><br />Tintin &amp; Co. had visited many countries and only a few had visited by myself. That made me think, should I follow his journeys to visit all countries mentioned in the comics? Tintin also visited the moon in his most famous iconic adventure <b>Destination Moon</b>. Can I go there too? Well... Let's see. Ha-ha.<br /><br />I brought another great novel, perhaps the most well-known and the best book by Mario Vargas Llosa. Reading <b>Conversation in Cathedral</b> in his native country, gave me goosebumps and sent chills down my spine!<br /><br /><br />PS: Fun fact, in the comic, Tintin used coca (yep, that famous plant) to keep the cursed archaeologist in a coma. In the real-life Cuzco City (the big city near Machu Picchu), I was relieved to learn that the tea is not an illegal narcotic, it’s simply a traditional remedy that averts the headaches and breathlessness some visitors experience at high altitude.<br /><br /><br /> <a href="https://melquiadescaravan.wordpress.com/2019/10/02/andes-mountains-bag-1/" rel="nofollow noopener">Part 1</a></span>
