<div id="review_1159241860" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1159241860" />
    <a title="John Gurney" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19356945-john-gurney"><img alt="John Gurney" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1365779791p2/19356945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1159241860?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Gurney" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Gurney" href="/user/show/19356945-john-gurney">John Gurney</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1159241860" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7576230017546596263">A chance encounter at a dog pound brings two former acquaintances together. They go to a bar called the Cathedral where Santiago, son of a once rich and powerful government minister, and Ambrosio, his father&apos;s former chauffeur, talk. Santiago wants to know what role his father had in the murder of his former mistress, a one-time Lima showgirl with shadowy connections. This 1969 book is rightly famous because, though the flashback Point-of-View narrative style takes some getting used to, it is a </span>
  <span id="freeText7576230017546596263" style="display:none">A chance encounter at a dog pound brings two former acquaintances together. They go to a bar called the Cathedral where Santiago, son of a once rich and powerful government minister, and Ambrosio, his father's former chauffeur, talk. Santiago wants to know what role his father had in the murder of his former mistress, a one-time Lima showgirl with shadowy connections. This 1969 book is rightly famous because, though the flashback Point-of-View narrative style takes some getting used to, it is a complex and gripping tale of sex, power, love, intrigue and corruption during the Odria dictatorship in 1950's Peru.<br /><br />This book is mostly dialogue and Vargas-Llosa's characters feel incredibly real because their conversations are so true-to-life. This is a long story, but it moves at a rapid pace. <i>Conversation in the Cathedral</i> is enjoyable- sometimes funny, sometimes saddening- but always worth reading.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7576230017546596263" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
